-- Sub-Saharan Africa Stocks: Mauritius Leasing, KenolKobil Move
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 2011-12-22T11:00:51Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-22/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-mauritius-leasing-kenolkobil-move.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index (SEMDEX)  advanced
for a second day, rising less than 0.1 percent to 1,860.13 by
the end of trading in Port Louis, the capital.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index (NSEASI)  added 0.7 percent to 54.69 by 1:51
p.m. in Nairobi, a second day of gains. The  Nigerian Stock
Exchange All-Share Index (NGSEINDX)  climbed for a fifth day, advancing 0.5
percent to 20,521.74 by 11:51 a.m. in Lagos. The  FTSE/Namibia
Overall Index (FTN098)  declined less than 0.1 percent to 829.77 by 12:52
p.m. in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index  slid
1.9 percent to 923.08 by 10:52 a.m. in Accra.  The following shares are among the active stocks in sub-
Saharan Africa, excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC)  , a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in nine African countries, advanced for a third day,
adding 1.1 percent to 9.45 shillings. Oil gained for a fourth
day in New York after U.S. crude inventories declined the most
in a decade, signaling tighter supplies in the world’s biggest
consumer of the commodity.  Mauritius Leasing Co. (MLC)  , which provides leasing
facilities for movable assets and equipment, rose for a second
day, climbing 4.2 percent to 7.4 rupees. The European Investment
Bank, the European Union’s long-term lending institution, said
this week it will provide 5 million euros in funding through
Mauritius Leasing Co. to support small and medium-sized
companies in the island nation.  To contact the reporters on this story:
